WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.540
So I'm going to start with where we're at now.

00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:10.600
So when I started as staff at Cleveland Clinic, we didn't even have Andromedon.

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:14.820
We were giving everyone Cyborg D, and then Andromedon got approved.

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:19.720
So Andromedon will take about half to 60% of patients and put them where we want amyloid

00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:22.080
patients to be, hematologic CR.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:27.080
But you'll note there that that median time to achieving that goal is a little over two

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:27.500
months.

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:33.640
When we look at the data that's out there in the real world for using BCMA, bispecific

00:00:33.640 --> 00:00:37.900
antibody of your choice, it is a drastically improved outcome.

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:45.680
So using this real-world data, we're seeing near 100%, 98% to 100% response rates.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:48.540
There's a very favorable safety profile in these patients.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:50.200
It's all relapsed refractory, AL.

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:55.280
Patients that are having real-world data, reports coming out from Mayo, the consortium,

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:56.580
our own internal data.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:58.080
And then we're going to publish our data.

00:00:58.240 --> 00:00:59.280
We'll combine with Tufts.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:06.580
The time to the first hematologic response with any of the BCMA bispecifics is 0.6 months.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:11.100
The best outcome in these patients occur in really three settings.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:16.900
Early disease detection, rapidly achieving complete hematologic remission, shutting down

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:24.600
new amyloid production, and then in the kappa only patients, being able to get access to

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:27.480
a viral monoclonal.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:33.340
So some work to be done there with the macrophage activating in the antifibril antibody space.

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:35.780
But right now, these two things are achievable.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:41.180
So our real-world data, this is 20 patients within our center.

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:44.220
19 of the patients do have efficacy and safety data.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:47.880
One of the patients passed during ramp-up, so we don't, unfortunately, have any sort

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:49.260
of long-term outcomes on that patient.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:54.800
We have 100% overall response rate with 100% of them achieving a rapid hematologic CR.

00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:57.920
The median time within our patient subset.

00:01:58.240 --> 00:01:59.420
It was 0.5.

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:01.500
And you see that range is very tight.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:06.820
So when you look at any other drug in amyloid, you don't see numbers anywhere close to this.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:13.140
The timing, again, of that median time to achieving a hematologic CR, 0.6.

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:16.500
Again, a very tight range around that window.

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:20.680
The median progression-free survival, median duration are not achieved.

00:02:20.680 --> 00:02:24.860
But I do have outcomes on several patients that are 24-plus months.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.180
And what's even more impressive is within our own dataset.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:30.780
Some of us were given continuous BCMA.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:37.520
And some of us started using a very short, limited duration of four to six months.

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:42.500
The 24-plus-month patients all received fixed duration.

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:45.480
They have not had any evidence of disease returning.

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:52.760
So these are the current studies that are on clinicaltrials.gov.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:57.760
So these are all investigator-initiated studies looking at the relapse refractory setting.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:07.400
There are also studies coming out from every player in the space.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:11.140
So we have Pfizer in the game, J&J, AbbVie, Regeneron.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:17.880
And now we have our first studies that are being pharma-sponsored coming out in amyloid,

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:20.220
looking at relapse refractory use with BCMA.

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:25.640
So the race is really on, and in particular, looking at these agents

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.580
at upfront newly-diagnosed amyloid.

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:33.940
So these are the studies that have actually opened in newly-diagnosed amyloid.

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:37.200
So there's one with teclistamab.

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:39.080
They're enrolling 25 patients.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:41.300
It's going to be a six-month fixed duration.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:46.820
There's another study looking at actually Mayo Stage 3B patients.

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:50.720
So the patients that traditionally could have higher risk or a little more fear,

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:54.000
but really the patients that probably would benefit the most from this drug class.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.120
They're enrolling 35 patients, and they're looking at a different outcome instead

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:58.120
of the other one.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:58.120
So these are the studies that have actually opened in newly-diagnosed amyloid.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:58.120
So there's one with teclistamab. They're enrolling 25 patients.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:58.120
It's going to be a six-month fixed duration. There's another study looking at actually Mayo Stage 3B patients.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:04.580
of the hematologic CR, they're looking at assessing a one-month reduction in the difference in the

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:11.160
free light chains. The current issues that exist within all of the newly diagnosed AL studies is

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:15.860
most of these patients, they don't live near an academic medical center. They're offering trials

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:20.040
in AL. So this is leading to slower recruitment to current studies. They're not allowing any prior

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:24.660
AL treatment. There's a very complicated schedule when you're doing combinations. So if you look

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:30.980
back at this top study, it's a combination with daratumumab. So there's going to be some more

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:38.800
kind of hurdles to overcome with getting these patients to a site that can give access to the

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:43.800
drug that's going to cure the majority of AL amyloid patients. The single agent, I think,

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:48.760
is going to be enough. We have tons of real-world data in that relapsed refractory setting.

00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:54.640
The DARA, this is going to be controversial to say, but it's unlikely to add any efficacy here.

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:59.780
It may, in fact, actually add to more infections and more complicated dosing schedule for patients.

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:05.100
The clone in AL is very different. It's ubiquitously positive for BCMA expression.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:11.380
It's a much lower clone. I don't think many of us are as worried about our T-cell fitness.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:16.840
We're just going to obliterate the clone safely and allow these patients to live their life.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:21.600
There's also too long of a duration of these study interventions, so two years versus six months.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:24.400
So this is...

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:30.800
This is the design that we are going to be going forward with as a research collaboration.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:36.560
So we're going to randomize a total of 64 patients, so 32 per arm,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.800
and it's looking at a dose strategy for scheduling. So is every two weeks or every four weeks?

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:52.180
Which of these is going to be able to provide enough of a quick reduction after step-up dosing?

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:54.640
And so the point of all of this is looking at all of our...

00:05:54.660 --> 00:06:01.020
Our real-world data and having patients achieve a rapid hematologic response within 0.6,

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:08.760
that covers the step-up dosing window, and then one additional full dose after step-up.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:14.120
That should get patients where they need to be, and within our own internal data set,

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:19.780
within the consortium data set, there are lots of patients who are receiving every four-week dosing.

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:24.180
That will allow these patients to be traveling further distances to come to get...

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:25.720
Treatment with us.

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:30.200
We could see a world, even as early as a couple years from now, where patients are coming,

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:38.740
getting two step-up doses, another full dose, and then four more monthly doses in their care.
